In xUnit, setup/teardown is handled through constructors, `IDisposable`, and `IClassFixture<T>` — not attributes:

| NUnit | xUnit equivalent |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` with a shared fixture class |

Here's your converted class:

```csharp
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // OneTimeSetUp
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // OneTimeTearDown
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)  // SetUp
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()                              // TearDown
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **`IClassFixture<T>`** — xUnit creates one `DatabaseFixture` instance per test class (same as `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]`)
- **Constructor** — runs before each test (replaces `[SetUp]`)
- **`IDisposable`** — runs after each test (replaces `[TearDown]`)
- If you need to share the fixture across *multiple* classes, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` with `[Collection]` instead
